recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird singing from midway up the canopy of a large oak tree near the forest edge.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 100 hz, order 3

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

Watched/recorded this bird for several minutes foraging in the interior branches of a large water oak (*Quercus nigra*). It flew from branch to branch gleaning from the foliage and occasionally hovering briefly to glean. The only vocalizations were these short scolding calls when Pine Warblers came too near the branch where the vireo was foraging.

#Habitat#
Lakeshore park with open lawns and some large trees, mostly water oak (*Quercus nigra*) and loblolly pine (*Pinus taeda*).

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Same individual as XC309321. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 100 hz, order 3

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Forneys Creek (near  Bryson City), Swain County, North Carolina
recordings.rmk:
In the background, running from ~2.0 sec through 6.0 sec. mark is a "wucka wucka, weeooo, wucka" sound.  This is Blue-headed Vireo, similar to XC30946.  At around 38 sec, mark begins a 6-note rattle: Winter Wren.  Golden-crowned Kinglet at 32 sec.


The birds I saw were Blue-headed Vireo, Dark-eyed Junco, Black-capped Chickadee.

Thanks.

recordings.loc: Algonquin Highlands, Haliburton County, Ontario
recordings.rmk: Trying to ID vireo singing in background. Couldn't find in canopy and as I would approach it would fly off 50 yards away. Heard singing in second growth forest dominated by tall deciduous trees. Have trouble with Vireos. This one sounds simpler, higher pitched, chopier and not as frequent as Red-eye Vireo. I thought it may be a migrant Philidelphia Vireo. Options would be REVI, BHVI or PHVI. Wondering if it can be IDed by this recording. http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23596515
